value.value: A raised projection on the calcaneus.
A raised projection on the lateral side of a calcaneus.
A raised projection on the medial side of a calcaneus.
The antorbital notch is a prominence of bone located anterolaterally of the antorbital fenestra.
At the dorsal part of the base of the calcaneal tuberoisty is a pointed process called the coracoid process.
A craniometric point at the junction of the posterior midline border of the vomer with the sphenoid bone on the sphenovomerine suture.
A suture joining a sphenoid bone with the alae of a vomer to form a schindylesis type of joint.
Any of the post-canine teeth, which are the multicuspidate molars or premolars used for shearing and grinding food in mammals.
An anatomical point on the antero-ventral margin of foramen magnum in the median plane.
A craniometric point on the ventral surface of the intersphenoid suture, along the midline of the skull.
A suture joining the basisphenoid bone and the presphenoid bone of a sphenoid bone.
A craniometric point that is the most anterior point in the midline on the alveolar process of the maxilla between the incisors (premaxilla bone).

definition.value: Often this point is midway between the median upper incisor teeth. In ruminants and pigs this point is projected into space.

value.value: The most dorsoanterior point on the supraoccipital crest in the medial plane.
An anatomical row consisting of adjacent cheek teeth.
A ridge or similar projection rising above the surface of an anatomical strucuture along the sagittal (midline) plane.
A craniometric point which is the furthest point from the glabella along the midline.
In pigs this point is projected into space as a point between a line connecting the aboral points of the right and left superior nuchal lines.
An anatomical point on the most lateral point of the frontal bone of tetrapods on the occipital side of the orbit.
The most lateral anatomical point of the zygomatic arch.
A process of bone extending downward from the jugular process of the occipital bone.
This process occurs in 0.5-2.0% of the human population.
A ridge or similar projection connected to the temporal lines and nuchal crest on the squamous part of the occipital bone. It bounds the posteroventral part of the temporal fossa.
Left part of the organism dorsal to a horizontal plane and bounded on one side by the same transverse plane.
Right part of the organism dorsal to a horizontal plane and bounded on one side by the same transverse plane.

A collection of Purkinje fibers that receives signals from the right and left bundle branches and innervates the ventricular cardiac muscle. The Purkinje fiber network creates synchronized contractions of the heart ventricles.
A forelimb that is on the right side of a pectoral complex.
A forelimb that is on the left side of a pectoral complex.
A hindlimb that is on the right side of a pelvic complex.
A hindlimb that is on the left side of a pelvic complex.

Hepatic serous coat; peritoneal covering of the liver, enclosing almost all except for a triangular area on its posterior surface (the 'bare area of the liver') and a smaller area where the liver and gallbladder are in direct contact.
Subserosal tissue of liver. A zone of areolar connective tissue lying beneath the serous coat of the liver and distinguished with difficulty from the fibrous capsule of Glisson.
Venule of villus of small intestine.
Arteriole of villus of small intestine.
A venule that is located in the anorectum.
An arteriole that is located in the anorectum.
An arteriole located in the colon.
An anatomical junction between two parts of the intestine.
A submucosal gland located in a bronchus.
A venule located in the colon.
A subdivision of the digestive tract in humans that includes the rectum, the anal canal and the anus.
A capillary that is part of the anorectum.
A capillary that is part of the colon.
A capillary that is part of a small intestine.
A submucosal gland found in a respiratory tract.
Red bone marrow located in the sternum.

Any of the smallest blood vessels where blood circulates within organ tissues. Microvessels include terminal arterioles, metarterioles, capillaries, and venules (but exclude lymphatic capillaries). Arterioles carry oxygenated blood to the capillaries, and blood flows out of the capillaries through venules into veins.
One or a subset of adjacent layers of the neocortex.
Collections of neurons in the central nervous system that have been demonstrated by histochemical fluorescence to contain the neurotransmitter norepinephrine (noradrenalin).
An anatomical system that eliminates waste products that arise as a result of metabolic activity.
Blood located in the placenta.
A portion of smooth muscle tissue that is part of an iliac vein.
A capillary that is part of the brain.
